project_descrip: Short: FAO SYRIA AND NEIGHBOURHOOD (2021-2023) Long: The expected long-term impact of the project is: The resilience, the food security and the livelihoods of the vulnerable small-scale women and men farmers, and unskilled workers from host communities and displaced Syrians are improved.To achieve this goal, the project will work with the MoA, Green Plan to support farmers' investments in land reclamation, water reservoirs and other on-farm complementary works.  This will be pursued through the support of the Green Plan funding mechanism, monitoring activities, developing the capacities of the farmers in collaboration with MoA extension services centres, with a priority given to women farmers.The project will be supporting 1 000 vulnerable small-scale women and men farmers' investments with matching grants (representing around 25 percent of the total initial cost of the investment paid by the farmer) for reclaiming their unproductive or abandoned lands, constructing water reservoirs for buffering water shortages, and/or other on-farm complementary works (terracing, retaining walls, planting of tree seedlings, installing more efficient drip irrigation systems, and fencing). Assuming that 70 percent of beneficiaries will enter into production after 3 years, it is expected that 700 beneficiary farmers will be producing at the end of the project. These matching grants will support investments that would generate a production value of about USD 3 to 9 million when farms reach maturity. It is expected that these investments will generate unskilled labour for host communities and displaced Syrians for the value of USD 1.0 to 1.5 million.

projecttitle: Oxfam IBIS Lot CIV strategic partnership 2018-2021
project_descrip: Short: OXFAM IBIS LOT CIV STRATEGIC PARTNERSHIP 2018-2021 Long: - Civil society organisations and alliances are strengthened to claim and exercise the universal right to qualityeducation and lifelong learning opportunities. This empowers poor and marginalised children, youth and adults to become active citizens, enabling political, economic, and social change.- Civil society organisations and alliances – particularly those involving women, youth and indigenous people –gain the power and legitimacy to hold governments to account. This leads to more sustainable development,improving economic and social justice.- Civil society – particularly women and youth – effectively engage in policy development and implementation of peacebuilding at national, regional and global level. This makes peace processes more inclusive and sustainable, and helps to prevent violent conflict and violent extremism.- Girls, boys, women and men affected by crisis gain basic life skills, knowledge and capacities to enhance theirrights leading to increased resilience through coordinated, community-led response.

projecttitle: Climate-Smart Agriculture and Market Development for Enhancing Livelihoods of Refugees and their Host Communities in Rwanda
project_descrip: Short: CLIMATE-SMART AGRICULTURE AND MARKET DEVELOPMENT FOR ENHANCING LIVELIHOODS OF REFUGEES AND THEIR HOST COMMUNITIES IN RWANDA Long: Building on the successful implementation of Misizi marshland project, the proposed replication of Misizi project model aims at improving livelihoods and self-reliance for more refugees and host communities, through facilitating access to arable land and agricultural inputs for market-oriented and climate-smart farming. Project phases include: 1) preparation in partnership with the Government of Rwanda and other partners, 2) Identifying 2-3 feasible value chain in partnership with private sector partners/companies, 3) Training/Agricultural Extension and business development advisory services, 4) transfer of productive assets (seeds/inputs/manure/irrigation), and 5) monitoring & evaluation.
shortdescription: CLIMATE-SMART AGRICULTURE AND MARKET DEVELOPMENT FOR ENHANCING LIVELIHOODS OF REFUGEES AND THEIR HOST COMMUNITIES IN RWANDA
channelname: United Nations Office of the High Commissioner for Refugees
channelreportedname: United Nations Office of the United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees
